{
  "text": "A possible direction for future work is the investigation of the relationships of the results proven here to the real-valued case. In fact certain notions of dimension, such as the Pollard's P -dimension, are naturally extended to classes of real-valued functions taking values in a bounded real interval (say 0; 1] for simplicity). A real-valued learning problem can be reduced to the multi-valued case through a discretization of the range 0; 1] into a set f0; : : : ; ng (see [CITATION_1] ). The number of discrete elements into which the continuous range is broken is proportional to 1 , where is the required bound on the error of the hypothesis. Also, the discretization does not increase the P -dimension of the original class, so the niteness of either the P -dimension or Vapnik's uniform P -dimension are su cient for robust learning in the real-valued case. On the other hand, some properties true in the discrete case are lost in the continuous one. For instance, while in the discrete case, the niteness of the P -dimension is equivalent to the niteness of the uniform P dimension, the class of monotone increasing functions on 0; 1] has in nite P -dimension but uniform P -dimension equal to 1.",
